<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-064-378  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 064 378.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Desktop Publishing  Jan 15 1990 v4 n5 p1(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple System 7: a smooth migration.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>Apple System 7: A Smooth Migration Apple has begun seeding its third-partysoftware developers with prerelease versions of System 7 for the Macintosh.andO;New features include font scaling from Royal-format outlines, virtual memoryand full 32-bit addressing.andP;  The new Finder makes software installation eveneasier and introduces &quot;aliases&quot; for file names and access paths.andP;  The CL/1database server access support and interapplication communication facilitieswill work across networks as well as in a single machine.andP;  In addition,System 7 will allow peer-to-peer file sharing among all Macs on a network,without requiring dedicated AppleShare file servers.andP;  Regrettably, the linelayout manager and the unified print architecture will not make the deadline.andM;Although publishers might ask for still more (such as full pre-emptivemultitasking, remote dial-in access, automatic database backup and low-costEthernet interfaces), for most software developers and users, System 7represents a manageable evolutionary step.andP;  It will help keep the Macintoshcompetitive in the race against OS/2, NextStep and Unix platforms.andO;</TEXT></DOC>